summary:
1. Demands that States prevent direct or indirect supply, sale, or transfer of arms and military equipment to non-governmental entities and individuals in Liberia;
2. Allows exemptions for supplies for the personal use of United Nations personnel, media, humanitarian and development workers, and associated personnel;
3. Demands that all States in West Africa prevent armed individuals and groups from using their territory to prepare and commit attacks on neighbouring countries and refrain from actions that might contribute to further destabilization;
4. (a) Decides that all States shall prevent the entry into or transit through their territories of individuals designated by the Committee who pose a threat to the peace process in Liberia or undermine peace and stability in Liberia and the subregion;
(b) Decides that measures in paragraph 4 (a) shall continue to apply to individuals already designated;
(c) Allows exemptions for humanitarian needs or where it furthers the objectives of the Council's resolutions;
5. Expresses readiness to terminate measures when the ceasefire is respected, disarmament and demobilization are completed, and stability is established in Liberia and the subregion;
6. Decides that all States shall prevent the direct or indirect import of all rough diamonds from Liberia;
7. Calls upon the National Transitional Government of Liberia to establish an effective Certificate of Origin regime for Liberian rough diamonds;
8. Expresses readiness to terminate measures when Liberia establishes a transparent and internationally verifiable Certificate of Origin regime;
9. Encourages Liberia to join the Kimberley Process;
10. Decides that all States shall prevent the import of round logs and timber products originating in Liberia;
11. Urges Liberia to establish authority over timber producing areas and ensure government revenues are used for legitimate purposes;
12. Expresses readiness to terminate measures when goals in paragraph 11 are achieved;
13. Encourages Liberia to establish oversight mechanisms for the timber industry;
14. Urges parties to the Comprehensive Peace Agreement to implement their commitments;
15. Calls upon States and organizations to offer assistance to Liberia;
16. Encourages assistance to Liberian civil aviation authorities;
17. Takes note of Liberia's establishment of a review committee;
18. Decides that measures in paragraphs 2, 4, 6, and 10 are established for 12 months.
